    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-02-04T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-02-04T22:00:00-05:00" n="466"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d466">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">891.77/715: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Iran</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schnare</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="4" xml:id="d466fn4">The substance of this telegram, and a
                        verbatim text of Tehran’s telegram No. 108, were transmitted to the
                        Ambassador in the Soviet Union in telegram No. 66, February 4, 11
                        p.m.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-02-04T23:00:00-04:00"
                            >February 4, 1943—11 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>65. Your 108, January 29. By telegram to Moscow sent January 19,<note n="5"
                        xml:id="d466fn5">No. 34, <ref target="#pg_439">p. 439</ref>.</note>
                    Department provided general information regarding purpose and character of
                    planned American operations. We think Russian Ambassador’s instructions may have
                    been sent prior to receipt of this information, and we are asking Moscow to
                    ascertain present attitude of Soviet Government.</p>
                <p>For your confidential information, Department does not consider it our
                    responsibility to engage in negotiations with Russians in connection with
                    operation of Iranian transport routes in question. If Soviet Government is still
                    reluctant to give its consent, Department will request Foreign Office at London
                    to take matter up.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
